# 🚀 Day 08 – Cloud Server Setup: AWS EC2, Docker & Nginx

Today was a huge milestone in my **90 Days DevOps Challenge** because I deployed my first web server on a real cloud instance.

## ☁️ What I Did Today

✅ Launched an Ubuntu EC2 instance on AWS
✅ Connected securely using SSH with a PEM key
✅ Updated the Linux server
✅ Installed Docker and verified the installation
✅ Installed and started the Nginx web server
✅ Verified that the Nginx service was running successfully
✅ Explored Nginx access and error logs
✅ Learned how to save logs into a separate file for troubleshooting

## 💻 Commands I Practiced

```bash
ssh -i Shree.pem ubuntu@<public-ip>
sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install docker.io -y
docker --version
sudo docker run hello-world
sudo apt install nginx -y
sudo systemctl status nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx
curl localhost
sudo cat /var/log/nginx/access.log
sudo cat /var/log/nginx/error.log
sudo nginx -t
sudo ss -tulnp | grep :80
```

## 🎯 Key Learnings

* Learned how to connect to a cloud server using SSH.
* Understood how to install and manage services on a Linux server.
* Learned to verify whether a service is running using `systemctl`.
* Explored Nginx log files for troubleshooting.
* Gained hands-on experience with a real AWS EC2 instance instead of a local virtual machine.

## 💡 Biggest Takeaway

Today I realized that DevOps is much more than writing commands. It's about provisioning servers, managing services, verifying deployments, and troubleshooting issues using logs. Working on a real cloud server gave me practical experience that closely matches real production environments.

